snippet: The newspaper returned with a depiction of the Prophet Muhammad on its cover, and, in some places, vendors reported that it had sold out before daybreak.
abstract: First issue of French newspaper Charlie Hebdo to be printed following terrorist attack on paper's Paris headquarters sells out across city and elsewhere as citizens and authorities express solidarity with paper and objection to terrorism; newspaper says it plans to print three million copies, compared to 60,000 sold week before attack, and may print as many as five million.

byline.original: By DAN BILEFSKY and ALAN COWELL
byline.contributor: Reporting was contributed by Daphné Anglès, Nicola Clark, Maïa de la Baume, David Jolly and Peter Sigal from Paris; Adam B. Ellick from Lyon, France; Michael R. Gordon from Geneva; and Sebnem Arsu from Istanbul.

lead_paragraph: The newspaper returned with a depiction of the Prophet Muhammad on its cover, and, in some places, vendors reported that it had sold out before daybreak.

headline.main: Robust Demand and Renewed Criticism as Charlie Hebdo Quickly Returns
headline.print_headline: Robust Demand and Renewed Criticism as Charlie Hebdo Quickly Returns
